segments.text: Same opportunities any male cadet would have, as you say, being in the army, in the band and whatever.
When Ms. Ingrass stepped up on the stage, obviously Dr. Miller recognized her.
And when they called her, just before they called her name, he turned to me and he said, I'm not going to shake hands with her.
And I said, Jarvis, I think that's a mistake.
I think you should.
You're representing Texas A&M and you need to do that to get your personal feelings about this."
And she walked up and I handed him the diploma and he would not shake hands with her.
And she didn't know what to do.
She turned to me and
Some people say I shook her hand.
I can't remember if I did or I didn't.
But anyway, I know it was an embarrassing moment.
I think my recollection is that you did not and that you said to her, ma'am, this is not part of my responsibility, something like that.
Okay.
And my recollection is that Don Carter then said, ma'am, would you please keep the line moving?
And so she walked on around.
She walked on, and she was the last one.
And her dean would have shaken hands with her at the exit of the stage, I think.
And I remember some hissing from corps members as they saw her coming up on the stage.
That, plus the fact that she's the last of the last of the last, causes everybody to stop and notice.
All eyes were there, and all eyes saw what happened.
Perfect.
What reaction do you remember afterward in the Letterman's Lounge or anywhere else?
Did you hear any comments?
Oh, yes.
Yes, I heard several comments that it was certainly not the proper thing to do.
I always felt that that was a big factor in Dr. Miller's future.
As I understand, when they summoned him over six weeks later,
the boardroom after their executive session to tell him that he his presidency was ended but that's the first thing that they said to him.
I don't know that.
I do know I knew one of the board members rather well during that regime and I do know that
that that was foremost in his mind, whether he was confronted with it at that particular time.
He was confronted with it, whether that was the time that he happened over at the Ramada Inn, did he not?
I believe.
I think that's right.
When he found out that he had been terminated, if I'm not mistaken, there was a cocktail party at the Ramada Inn, and that was when he learned about it.
And now, in the Letterman's Lounge, right after that commencement,
I heard a couple of board members mumbling in the other direction.
I heard them saying, serves are right, should have, you know, serves are right.
Well, they would have been from that particular group that we talked about earlier and wanted to take their Aggie rings off, and females were admitted to A&M.
Right.
Let's see.
What are some things you remember happening that, now we're on positive, happening in the audience during commencements?
Well, of course, I always truly enjoy hearing sometimes very loud and exciting responses from parents when their son or their daughter would walk across the stage.
Such things as, you finally made it.
Gee, Mama and I can enjoy a vacation.
or things like that.
Also, you heard a lot of funny responses and also saw some really interesting things with the type of signs that the candidates would put on top of their hats.
Do you remember any?
Oh, well, there was always needing a job or I'm for hire or those kind of things or hey, Mom, I did it.
Hey, Dad, I did it or things like that.
My favorite of all is one that said simply, hell froze over.
That's good.
That's good.
Of the presidents that you observed at commencement, which ones did it best?
It can be plural.
I didn't say one, but one.
I understand.
You mean...
The commencement ceremony.
All their participation and everything.
Well, Jack Williams was very smooth up there.
He was a wonderful speaker.
Frank Vandiver was a wonderful speaker.
And I think, of course, you know Frank had a different, something that I'll always remember him by.
He wore gloves when he shook hands with the students.
And I think no other president did that, but he always had a glove on.
Let's see.
Okay.
Who can't see?
After Vandiver, we had... Mobley?
Mobley.
And then after Mobley, we had...
Wait a minute, Mobley came.
I never did work with Mobley, no.
No, Dr. Vandiver was still there when I left.
Yeah, he was there.
I worked with, I worked with, well I worked with General Rutter, and I worked then with Ludeke, then Williams, then Jarvis, and then Chick, I mean the engineer.
the interim president, Chuck Sampson.
Dr. Sampson.
I got the wrong ballot on there.
I would say overall speaking, when you look at the, I mean all of them loved the congratulations and shaking hands with the students.
I mean every one of them loved that.
But overall speaking, if you look at all aspects of it, I think Dr. Williams and Dr. Vandiver really did a superb job.
And I guess a lot of that has to do with those two gentlemen were outstanding speakers.
They were both historians.
They were both historians, exactly.
All right.
Dr. Williams has the heart attack and when he recovers and did, during that period Mr. Freeman was the interim.
Did that make any changes in the way y'all operated?
No.
Okay.
Then Williams comes back and the board then recreates the system administration and he
They make him the chancellor and the board selects Dr. Miller as the president.
Did that change?
Are you speaking to graduation or are you speaking to the whole operation?
No, I don't recall that it did at all.
No, I don't.
You and Ed and Don.
We were still there.
Dr. Miller seemed to be pleased with what we were doing.

Dr. Miller was very instrumental in getting us the space over in Heaton Hall and getting us moved in there, of course, which was certainly something that was overdue for us because we'd gotten so crowded.
When did we really start?
electronic computing in the whole registrar operations?
Well, let's see.
In about, we had some terminals when we were still in the Koch building.
I would say about 1970, 72, 73,
We really started getting our equipment and that sort of thing.
By the time we got into Heaton, we almost had a terminal for everybody who needed one.
Today, ten years ago when I left there, at that time we had accomplished where every faculty member had a terminal by 1988.
I am very comfortable with the fact that I set out to do something that I thought was so needed, and that was to automate that system, and it accomplished it.
I feel very comfortable, and I'm very appreciative of people like Chuck McCandless, who was a big proponent for us.
Well, you know, all of our people in the vice president's offices always found the VP and the provost to be very generous with us and give us most of the time what we asked for.
And computing cost a lot of money.
I mean, it took a ton of money to put this online system up and this touch home registration.
Haskalawa always viewed a registrar's office as being an academic service unit.
Sure.
That's what it is.
Academic service for the students, the staff, and the faculty.
And it costs money to deliver those kinds of things.

I just think today how wonderful it is that a faculty member can sit there in their office and through a terminal they can know everything they need to know about a student's board of the academic program.
They don't have to have all these files and folders and all that sort of stuff.
Where did you turn as you were trying to make this conversion?
To what institution or corporation did you turn for?
for advice and counsel?
Well, the first people that I contacted when I was speaking earlier, when I first started to get this out of Savisa Hall and going to this pre-registration plan was Purdue.
And I spent many hours at Purdue just trying to see if what they were doing would fit the Texas A&M.
The thing that we were always able to do here,
There were a lot of schools throughout the country that were giving what I call a partial registration opportunity to a student.
And that would be, most of them were doing nothing but scheduling their academic classes.
And they would get their bill in the mail, and then they'd have to go all over campus to the police,
to the library, to the ticket office where to pay all this stuff.
And I didn't see that that was helping us any.
Because after all, even in a field house registration like we had at Sabisa Dining Hall, when a kid walked out that back door, he was through, or she.
They could pay all their fees and everything in one deal.
So I wanted that same thing electronically done.
So we were able to do that through our early pre-registration system, although it still wasn't what I wanted.
And then when touch-tone came in and the telephone industry upgraded and we were able to transmit all this data by means of the phone line, Brigham Young had the first touch-tone registration system.
So I went out there and spent quite a bit of time with them.
But as it would have it, they were doing nothing but the academic schedule.
A student would get on the phone, key in, and they'd get their schedule mailed to them.
But when they got their schedule, they'd still have to go back on campus and go buy their tickets, their athletic tickets, their dining and all that.
They still had four or five different places they had to go to.
So I wasn't satisfied.
I was satisfied with the academic schedule, but I wasn't satisfied with it.
It was not complete.
So Texas A&M was the first institution in the country that gave a student the complete registration process by means of Texas A&M.
And also to be the size that it was.
Do you remember what year that was?
Well, let's see.
We started that committee in about 84, which I was chairman of.
And we had that thing completely implemented by, I'm going to say about 1987.
It was up and running at least a year and a year and a half before I left.
Now there have been a lot of things added to it since then that we had planned at that time.
This automated degree program that we talked about earlier had come in since then, but we had that in our package.
That was all part of our plan.
But I guess the greatest compliment that I ever had relative to Touchstone registration was one day after Christmas when we started back for the spring semester.
A phone call came in, and this guy got on the phone, and he said, Mr. Lacey, I'm so-and-so, class of
whatever it was, in the 50s.
And he said, I just want to tell you how wonderful it is that my daughter could register while she was at home.
It did it by telephone.
He said, I'm one of the people that walked through Sabisa Dining Hall.
I said, well, I know what you're comparing it to then.
And he said, it's just great.
He said, we want to express our appreciation to you.
And I said, well, thank you very much.
We appreciate your call.
He said, don't you want to know where I'm calling from?
I said, well, where are you calling from?
He said, London, England.
Oh, my goodness, how good.
So I said, hey, wonderful.
And truly, if you have a touchstone phone, you can register from anywhere in the world.
I remember our son, our number four, doing it from Columbia, Missouri one semester, and he got exactly what he wanted.
Then the next day he decided he wanted to change the schedule.
I'm going to change some hours.
He got on the phone and in less than 30 minutes.
He had it done.
He had it all done entirely differently.
And it suited his fancy.
And I thought that if you can have that student walk into class the first day feeling comparatively optimistic about the hour, the course, the instructor.
In other words, they selected it.
Correct.
There's a chance for it being better.
Got to be happy.
Yeah.
Got to be happy.

And see, the other wonderful thing about that too, Haskell, which you saw, or you would appreciate this, being a faculty member, that roster, if that faculty member got that first morning, that first day of class, was absolutely excellent.
Oh yeah, because it was all real time, and if a kid decided he wanted to drop a course on Sunday night, before we printed those things,
His name was off the list.

And you know, back to what I said earlier about being, when I was a student here, having those two places that I wanted to do something about, the registrar's office and the fiscal office, I think we've made a lot of progress there because
It took me a while to get the fiscal people to come along, but I did.
And they agreed to automate all of the finances and the student bills and that sort of thing.
I wasn't going to put it in unless I could get that because I felt like we need to give the student complete registration.
And as a result, I understand today that they've automated a lot.
You don't see the green jade in the fiscal office.
Looking back, what are the key decisions that affected the registrar's operation that you can think of that now, in hindsight, were key decisions?
Plus or minus?
Well,
And I don't know, I have to be a little bit personal about what I do when I say what I'm fixing to say.
We raised the Office of Admissions and Records to a higher level than it was when I came in.
And I don't want to be critical about that.
And there were people like you and McKinley that we worked with that helped us do that.
We gained some position on the campus.
I think we were looked on in the earlier years, as I said, as a necessary evil, just thorn in everybody's side.
And I wanted to change that image to show that we were
a service unit, an academic service unit.
We wanted to work with the people out there.

And I think people like John Calhoun and Williams who supported and recognized that we needed to be, and Ed Cooper, Ed Cooper had a lot to do with it, to get us up there where we were recognized and we were heard and we had a say in things that were important to Texas A&M University.
such as classroom utilization.

I mean, you know, they were building buildings up there and not asking anybody any questions at all long before Chuck McCandlish got there, you know, and where we had then some data to say, hey, don't come in here and tell me you need another history building or another English building.
Let me show you right now what you're not using.
We couldn't do that.
It was again back to that similar type of attitude
Well, I need to teach my class in this building.
Well, we need a new building for mechanical engineering just because we need a new building for mechanical engineering.
And there's a lot of politics and all that, and you and I focused on that.
But I think we got administrations to recognize these people.

are necessary in the management of this university, and they've got a lot of data over there that can be very helpful to us in making some critical decisions before we go out here to Hawthorne and start asking for money.

And so, and I think a lot of that has to do with personality, you know, and being able to sit down and I guess one of the things that I always respected about our administration here, always felt like
that if you could get in there, and once we got to that level, get in there, they would listen to you.
And you could make your point.
And, you know, if it was legitimate, I mean, I never felt like that I went down and asked them for something that wasn't necessary.
I learned that a long, long time ago.
That, you know, I feel like that we as

employees of public institutions that have tax dollars that are we're responsible for need to be responsible for and need to be uh you know not here just asking because i mean am in my whole career in texas a m university never once did i ever feel that we didn't have the money to do something no we were always told a lot of stuff but that's fine good

But I just felt, I feel like, and I think one of the big things that really is a factor there when we were able to say, hey, let us schedule these classes and let us show you what kind of classroom utilization we can come out with, was a big decision that helped us.
There were many others.
One thing that I was always blessed with my job up there, and maybe it's kind of hard for me to answer your question, I have to assume that we did a good job because nobody was ever pushing us.
I mean, really.
You know, the 26 years I worked there, I never, ever had
for one major money in the domain capital of my life.
You said one time.
Can you?
Dr. Wernert.
And Dr. Wernert and I are good friends today.
And I think it was maybe because, you know, I mean, it was just a point of... And if he were sitting in that room, he'd say, well, hey, you know, it shouldn't have ever happened.
But I feel...
I just always felt that we were honest and honorable, forthright in what we were coming in there to ask people about, and most of the time they supported us.
And that's a compliment on both sides, to them and to me.
Proudest moments?
Some events you can remember and say, ooh, yeah, yeah.
Well, we were extremely proud.
when we got into our new facility over there.
I mean, that was, you know, we had a building now that belonged, I don't want to be talking about both sides of my mouth when I say belonged to us.
I don't mean it in the sense that I talked about earlier, but we had space.
We had adequate space.
And another proud moment was when it had again to do with the registration, was when they came and said, hey, here's a pavilion, be with it.
And I was the project coordinator on that building.
Dying it like a wound.
Now who made the decision not to tear that down, but to save it?
Because there had to be somebody.
Yeah, there was.
Well, let's see.
Was McCandless still here?
McCandless?
Oh yes.
Oh yeah, McCandless was here then.
Yes.
I was trying to think who the president would have been then, I guess.
Was it Miller?
No.
Wasn't Miller?
No.
Because I'm still here.
You're still here.
Okay.
And it's after me.
I think so.
Okay, and it's after you?
I think so.
So it's... Would you leave 80?
So it's Chuck Sampson or Vanderer, I guess.
You know, that's what I'm...
I'm sorry.
I'm completely lapsed on that.
I know I worked with Chuck on that thing, you know.
Of course, Chuck was also involved in that, uh, uh, well, no, he left, though, Danny, when he, when he left Provost Office, he and, he and Eaton went to Iowa State.
Iowa State, didn't they?
Well, I'll have to, let me, let me see if I can get a, get a little more information.
I may be some fill-in I'll do for you when we get there.
Other proud moments you recall?
Uh,
Well, I've already talked about this some, but the proudest of my whole administration up there was the institution of the student automated records.
I don't know where we are today.
I suspect we're still at the top, but we were at the top then, and we should be there now.
And, you know, I mean, I can remember high school when it took a kid three, four weeks to get a transcript after the grade turned in.
They're getting them now the next day, you know.
And they're in the mail and gone.
And that's just, in my business, that's very, very important.
And I know we're miles ahead of what a lot of schools do.
All right.
If you could go back, are there anything
Is there anything or things you'd like, wish you could change, given hindsight?
No.
And I'll tell you why, again, why I feel that way.
I feel that way because I've only had two jobs in my entire lifetime.
One of them was the Cypress Firebanks and the rest of them was the Texas A&M.
But I can also tell you this.
I was very close nationwide to my colleagues in this business.
When I was much younger in this field, I went to all of those national meetings, and I stayed very much up to date on all of them.
And I came home time after time after time, thinking,
everybody that I could think that had given me my job at that time, because I would not have been employed in those schools.
Not only because of the way, necessarily of the lack of facilities, or the lack of money, or the lack of poor administration, or the student body.
The student body probably comes first.
We've got, had, in my lifetime,
the best student body in the world.
And if you recall, when all the upheaval was going on in Kent State and other places across the country, one day, I looked out my window and I caught this group of students out around Southern.
And this was during the time when the moratoriums were going and all that stuff, Vietnam.
I walked over there just to see.
very friendly discussion going on between the cowboys and the cadet corps on one side and the few hippies we had on the other side.
But what they had to say, I enjoyed listening to because they both were making third points and they were decent about it.
And it was ended and it was gone.
You know, we didn't have
students walking in the president's office and grabbing him by the tie and throwing him out in the hall and locking and taking over and all that kind of stuff.
So, and then having the kind of administrators that we had that supported us and listened to us and the student body we had and all the wonderful people that we had around us to work with.
I'll go back through it again and we'll change things.
Okay, we're getting close to the end.

Let's make believe that somebody walked up to you and handed you a check for a lot of money, and we'll say six figures at least, and say, here, you can give this to Texas A&M, and you can specify what unit, what part of the university it's going to go to.
What would that do?
Well, I'm big on scholarships.
For what?
Needy.
Regardless of their major?
Needy students, regardless of their major.
I believe very strongly in everybody having an opportunity for an education.
And then I also think that
certain amounts of it would be necessary to cut to research.
That may sound a little bit strange coming from me, but I do know how valuable research is.
I think sometimes maybe we get a little overboard on it.
That's just a personal opinion.
But I think it's extremely important.
I would have difficulty in putting it into buildings and that sort of thing because I think that's what the state of Texas should be doing.
But I would put it into that.
